# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cis-benchmarks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In configuration management, a **baseline** is an agreed description of the attributes of a product, at a point in time, which serves as a basis for defining change.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] A change is a movement from this baseline state to a next state.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] The identification of significant changes from the baseline state is the central purpose of baseline identification.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Typically, significant states are those that receive a formal approval status, either explicitly or implicitly.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] An approval status may be attributed to individual items, when a prior definition for that status has been established by project leaders, or signified by mere association to a particular established baseline.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Nevertheless, this approval status is usually recognized publicly.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] A baseline may be established for the singular purpose of marking an approved configuration item, e.g. a project plan that has been signed off for execution.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Associating multiple configuration items to such a baseline indicates those items as also being approved.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Baselines may also be used to mark milestones.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] A baseline may refer to a single work product, or a set of work products that can be used as a logical basis for comparison.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Most baselines are established at a fixed point in time and serve to continue to reference that point (identification of state).
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] However, some baselines, dynamic baselines, are established to carry forward as a reference to the item itself regardless of any changes to the item.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] These latter baselines evolve with the progression of the work effort but continue to identify notable work products in the project.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Retrieving such a dynamic baseline obtains the current revision of only these notable items in the project.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] While marking approval status covers the majority of uses for a baseline, multiple fixed baselines may also be established to monitor the progress of work through the passage of time.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In this case, each baseline is a visible measure through an endured team effort, e.g. a series of developmental baselines.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] This progression is revealed when the baselines are compared with each other.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] A baseline may also be established as the basis for subsequent exclusive activities when the baselined products have met certain criteria.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] For example, certain activities reserved for items with a prior formal approval, such as formal change control procedures.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Baselines themselves are valued not only to identify the notable state of work product(s) but also provide historical views of how work product elements have progressed together over time.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] For this reason, baseline identification, monitoring, and retrieval are critical to the success of configuration management, and ultimately, project quality.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Conversely, the configuration of a project includes all of its baselines, the status of the configuration, all audits, and all metrics collected.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] The current configuration refers to the current status, current audit, and current metrics.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Similarly, but less common, a baseline may refer to all items in a project.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] This may include the latest revision of all items or only specific revisions of all items in the project, depending on the nature of the baseline, dynamic or fixed respectively.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Once retrieved, the baseline may be compared to a particular configuration or another baseline.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In configuration management, the configuration of a project is not the same as a baseline in the project but the two could coincide.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Fixed baselines often coincide with or signify project milestones, such as the set of items at a particular certifying review.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Though common in software revision control systems as labels' or tags, the existence of baselines is found in several other technology-related domains.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Baselines can be found in UML modeling systems and business rule management systems, among others.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In addition to the field of hardware and software engineering, baselines can be found in medicine (e.g. monitoring health progress), politics (e.g. statistics), physics and chemistry (e.g. observations and changes), finance (e.g. budgeting), and others.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In the process of performing configuration management, configuration items (or work products) may be assigned a baseline so as to establish them as having a certain status.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In this sense, to baseline a work product may require certain change(s) to the work product to ensure it conforms to the characteristics associated with the baseline referenced.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] This varies upon context, but in many cases this requires that the work product is "reset" to an initial (possibly inherently approved) state from which work may proceed.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] In many environments, baselines are controlled such that certain subsequent activities against work products in that baseline are either prohibited or permitted.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] These activities are selected and controlled, and again, depending upon the configuration management system, are also monitored.
[src:cis-benchmarks/baseline-configuration-management] Consequently, baselines are ordinarily subjected to configuration management audits.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] In computing, a **benchmark** is the act of running a computer program, a set of programs, or other operations, in order to assess the relative performance of an object, normally by running a number of standard tests and trials against it.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] The term *benchmark* is also commonly utilized for the purposes of elaborately designed benchmarking programs themselves.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking is usually associated with assessing performance characteristics of computer hardware, for example, the floating point operation performance of a CPU, but there are circumstances when the technique is also applicable to software.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Software benchmarks are, for example, run against compilers or database management systems (DBMS).
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks provide a method of comparing the performance of various subsystems across different chip/system architectures.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking as a part of continuous integration is called Continuous Benchmarking.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] As computer architecture advanced, it became more difficult to compare the performance of various computer systems simply by looking at their specifications.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Therefore, tests were developed that allowed comparison of different architectures.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks are designed to mimic a particular type of workload on a component or system.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Synthetic benchmarks do this by specially created programs that impose the workload on the component.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Application benchmarks run real-world programs on the system.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] While application benchmarks usually give a much better measure of real-world performance on a given system, synthetic benchmarks are useful for testing individual components, like a hard disk or networking device.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks are particularly important in CPU design, giving processor architects the ability to measure and make tradeoffs in microarchitectural decisions.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] For example, if a benchmark extracts the key algorithms of an application, it will contain the performance-sensitive aspects of that application.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Running this much smaller snippet on a cycle-accurate simulator can give clues on how to improve performance.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Since around 1995, the SPEC collection of benchmarks have become widely used.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Computer companies are known to tune their systems to improve performance on benchmark tests that are not representative of real world usage.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks have been improved to more closely mimic real world usage, so that any tuning carries over to application performance.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Software vendors also use benchmarks in their marketing, such as the "benchmark wars" between rival relational database makers in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Companies commonly report only those benchmarks (or aspects of benchmarks) that show their products in the best light.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] They also have been known to mis-represent the significance of benchmarks, again to show their products in the best possible light.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] When performance is critical, the only benchmark that matters is the target environment's application suite.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Features of benchmarking software may include recording/exporting the course of performance to a spreadsheet file, visualization such as drawing line graphs or color-coded tiles, and pausing the process to be able to resume without having to start over.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking is not easy and often involves several iterative rounds in order to arrive at predictable, useful conclusions.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Interpretation of benchmarking data is also extraordinarily difficult.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] There are seven vital characteristics for benchmarks.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Representativeness: Benchmark performance metrics should be broadly accepted by industry and academia.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Equity: All systems should be fairly compared.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Repeatability: Benchmark results can be verified.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Cost-effectiveness: Benchmark tests are economical.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Scalability: Benchmark tests should work across systems possessing a range of resources from low to high.
[src:cis-benchmarks/benchmark-computing] Transparency: Benchmark metrics should be easy to understand.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The **Center for Internet Security** (**CIS**) is a US 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization, formed in October 2000.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The organization is headquartered in East Greenbush, New York, US, with members including large corporations, government agencies, and academic institutions.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS began as a volunteer-based initiative to create actionable, consensus based security configuration benchmarks aimed at helping organizations of all sizes decrease cyber risk.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Over time, CIS evolved into a significant entity in cybersecurity coordination at the national level.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] In 2003, it collaborated with the SANS Institute to establish the CIS Controls, a ranked collection of best practices aimed at protecting against prevalent cyber threats.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The organization also established a Center (MS-ISAC), a federally supported organization to assist U.S state, local, tribal, and territorial (SLTT) governments in identifying addressing, and averting cyber incidents.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS became registered as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization located in East Greenbush, New York, with an additional office in Washington, D.C.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The governance of CIS consists of a Board of Directors featuring cybersecurity experts various industries.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The board offers strategic guidance, while daily operations are overseen by a Chief Executive Office and an executive team.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] As of 2025, John Gilligan is President and CEO of CIS, and he has emphasized the significance of strengthening collaboration with DHS, CISA, and other global cybersecurity entities.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS has several program areas, including MS-ISAC, CIS Controls, CIS Benchmarks, CIS Communities, and CIS CyberMarket.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Through these program areas, CIS works with a wide range of entities, including those in academia, the government, and both the private sector and the general public to increase their online security by providing them with products and services that improve security efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The Multi-State Information Sharing and Analysis Center (MS-ISAC) is a "round-the-clock cyber threat monitoring and mitigation center for state and local governments" operated by CIS under a cooperative agreement with the U.S.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Department of Homeland Security (DHS), Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA).
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The MS-ISAC was established in late 2002, and officially launched in January 2003, by William F.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Pelgrin, then Chief Security Officer of the state of New York.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Beginning from a small group of participating states in the Northeast, MS-ISAC came to include all 50 U.S.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] States and the District of Columbia, as well as U.S.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] State, Local, Tribal, and Territorial (SLTT) governments.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] In order to facilitate its expanding scope, in late 2010, MS-ISAC "transitioned into a not-for-profit status under the auspices of the Center for Internet Security." In March 2025, CISA ended funding for MC-ISAC.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] MS-ISAC "helps government agencies combat cyberthreats and works closely with federal law enforcement", and is designated by DHS as a key cyber security resource for the nation's SLTT governments.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The MS-ISAC offers a variety of federally funded, no-cost, cybersecurity products and services to its members through the DHS CISA cooperative agreement.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] It also offers fee-based products and services for SLTT members who want additional protection in addition to what is offered under the cooperative agreement.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The EI-ISAC is operated by the Center for Internet Security, Inc. under the same cooperative agreement with DHS CISA as the MS-ISAC.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] By nature of election offices being SLTT organizations, each EI-ISAC member is automatically an MS-ISAC member and can take full advantage of the products and services provided to both ISACs.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The mission of the EI-ISAC is to improve the overall cybersecurity posture of SLTT election offices, through collaboration and information sharing among members, the U.S.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) and other federal partners, and private sector partners are the keys to success.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] And the EI-ISAC comprises representatives from SLTT election offices and contractors supporting SLTT election infrastructure.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Formerly known as the SANS Critical Security Controls (SANS Top 20) and the CIS Critical Security Controls, the CIS Controls as they are called today is a set of 18 prioritized safeguards to mitigate the most prevalent cyber-attacks against today's modern systems and networks.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The CIS Controls are grouped into Implementation Groups (IGs), which allow organizations to use a risk assessment in order to determine the appropriate level of IG (one through three) that should be implemented for their organization.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The CIS Controls can be downloaded from CIS, as can various mappings to other frameworks such as the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Cybersecurity Framework (CSF), NIST Special Publication (SP) 800-53, and many others.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS also offers a free hosted software product called the CIS Controls Assessment Tool (CIS-CAT) that allows organizations to track and prioritize the implementation of the CIS Controls.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The CIS Controls advocate "a defense-in-depth model to help prevent and detect malware".
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] A May 2017 study showed that "on average, organizations fail 55% of compliance checks established by the Center for Internet Security", with more than half of these violations being high severity issues.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] In March 2015, CIS launched CIS Hardened Images for Amazon Web Services, in response to "a growing concern surrounding the data safety of information housed on virtual servers in the cloud".
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The resources were made available as Amazon Machine Images, for six "CIS benchmarks-hardened systems", including Microsoft Windows, Linux and Ubuntu, with additional images and cloud providers added later.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS released Companion Guides to CIS Controls, recommendations for actions to counter cybersecurity attacks, with new guides having been released in October and December 2015.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] In April 2018, CIS launched an information security risk assessment method to implement CIS Controls, called CIS RAM.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Version of CIS RAM v2.0 was released October 2021.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS Benchmarks are a collaboration of the Consensus Community and **CIS SecureSuite** members (a class of CIS members with access to additional sets of tools and resources).
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The Consensus Community is made up of experts in the field of IT security who use their knowledge and experience to help the global Internet community.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS SecureSuite members are made up of several different types of companies ranging in size, including government agencies, colleges and universities, nonprofits, IT auditors and consultants, security software vendors and other organizations.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS Benchmarks and other tools that CIS provides at no cost allow IT workers to create reports that compare their system security to universal consensus standard.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] This fosters a new structure for internet security that everyone is accountable for and that is shared by top executives, technology professionals and other internet users throughout the globe.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Further, CIS provides internet security tools with a scoring feature that rates the configuration security of the system at hand.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] For example, CIS provides SecureSuite members with access to CIS-CAT Pro, a "cross-platform Java app" which scans target systems and "produces a report comparing your settings to the published benchmarks".
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] This is intended to encourage and motivate users to improve the scores given by the software, which bolsters the security of their internet and systems.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The universal consensus standard that CIS employs draws upon and uses the accumulated knowledge of skillful technology professionals.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Since internet security professionals volunteer in contributing to this consensus, this reduces costs for CIS and makes it cost effective.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS CyberMarket is a "collaborative purchasing program that serves U.S.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] State, Local, Tribal, and Territorial (SLTT) government organizations, nonprofit entities, and public health and education institutions to improve cybersecurity through cost-effective group procurement".
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The intent of the CIS CyberMarket is to combine the purchasing power of governmental and nonprofit sectors to help participants improve their cybersecurity condition at a lower cost than they would have been able to attain on their own.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The program assists with the "time intensive, costly, complex, and daunting" task of maintaining cybersecurity by working with the public and private sectors to bring their partners cost-effective tools and services.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] The combined purchasing opportunities are reviewed by domain experts.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS CyberMarket, like the MS-ISAC, serves government entities and non-profits in achieving greater cyber security.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] On its "resources" page, multiple newsletters and documents are available free of charge, including the "Cybersecurity Handbook for Cities and Counties".
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS Communities are "a volunteer, global community of IT professionals" who "continuously refine and verify" CIS best practices and cybersecurity tools.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] To develop and structure its benchmarks, CIS uses a strategy in which members of the organization first form into teams.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] These teams then each collect suggestions, advice, official work and recommendations from a few participating organizations.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Then, the teams analyze their data and information to determine what the most vital configuration settings are that would improve internet system security the most in as many work settings as possible.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Each member of a team constantly works with their teammates and critically analyzes and critiques a rough draft until a consensus forms among the team.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Before the benchmark is released to the general public, they are available for download and testing among the community.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] After reviewing all of the feedback from testing and making any necessary adjustments or changes, the final benchmark and other relevant security tools are made available to the public for download through the CIS website.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] This process is so extensive and so carefully executed that thousands of security professionals across the globe participate in it.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] CIS has since grown to have hundreds of members with varying degrees of membership and cooperates and works with a variety of organizations and members at both the national and international levels.
[src:cis-benchmarks/center-for-internet-security] Some of these organizations include those in both the public and private sectors, government, ISACs and law enforcement.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:cis-benchmarks/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] In computer security, **hardening** or **system hardening** is usually the process of securing a system by making it a 'hard target' by reducing its attack surface vulnerabilities.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] The attack surface is larger when a system performs more functions; in principle a single-function system is more secure than a multipurpose one.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Hardening is considered an important component of cybersecurity.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Reducing available ways of attack typically includes changing default passwords, the removal of unnecessary software, unnecessary usernames or logins, and the disabling or removal of unnecessary services.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] It may also involve patching vulnerabilities and switching off ancillary services that are not essential.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Hardening measures can also include setting up intrusion prevention systems, disabling or restricting accounts, reducing file system permissions, using encrypted network connections and enabling host-based network security.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Binary hardening is a security technique in which binary executables are analyzed and modified to protect against common exploits.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Binary hardening is independent of compilers and involves the entire toolchain.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] For example, one binary hardening technique is to detect potential buffer overflows and to substitute the existing code with safer code.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] The advantage of manipulating binaries is that vulnerabilities in legacy code can be fixed automatically without the need for source code, which may be unavailable or obfuscated.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Secondly, the same techniques can be applied to binaries from multiple compilers, some of which may be less secure than others.
[src:cis-benchmarks/hardening-computing] Binary hardening often involves the non-deterministic modification of control flow and instruction addresses so as to prevent attackers from successfully reusing program code to perform exploits.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] The **CIS Controls** (formerly called the **Center for Internet Security Critical Security Controls for Effective Cyber Defense**) is a publication of best practice guidelines for computer security.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] The project was initiated early in 2008 in response to extreme data losses experienced by organizations in the US defense industrial base.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] The publication was initially developed by the SANS Institute and released as the "SANS Top 20." Ownership was then transferred to the Council on Cyber Security (CCS) in 2013, and then transferred to Center for Internet Security (CIS) in 2015.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] CIS released version 8 of the CIS Controls in 2021.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] The guidelines consist of 18 (originally 20) key actions, called critical security controls (CSC), that organizations should implement to block or mitigate known attacks.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] The controls are designed so that primarily automated means can be used to implement, enforce and monitor them.
[src:cis-benchmarks/the-cis-critical-security-controls-for-effective-cyber-defense] The security controls give no-nonsense, actionable recommendations for cyber security, written in language that’s easily understood by IT personnel.
